abstract  ="The co-ordination properties of the tridentate ligand 2{,}2[prime or minute] : 6[prime or minute]{,}2[double prime]-terpyridine (terpy) make it an ideal structural unit from which to assemble co-ordination oligomers and polymers with a linear connectivity about the metal centre. The dinucleating {'}back-to-back{'} 2{,}2[prime or minute] : 6[prime or minute]2[double prime]-terpyridine ligands 6[prime or minute]{,}6[double prime]-bis(2-pyridyl)-2{,}2[prime or minute] : 4[prime or minute]{,}4[double prime] : 2[double prime]{,}2[triple prime]-quaterpyridine L and 1{,}4-bis(2{,}2[prime or minute] : 6[prime or minute]{,}2[double prime]-terpyridin-4[prime or minute]-yl)benzene L give rise to a linear connectivity at the ligand{,} whereas 1{,}3{,}5-tris(2{,}2[prime or minute] : 6[prime or minute]{,}2[double prime]-terpyridin-4[prime or minute]-yl)benzene L is a trinucleating species which can give rise to arrays with a connectivity of three at the ligand. The co-ordination oligomers [(X-terpy)RuLRu(X-terpy)](L = L or L) and [{(X-terpy)Ru}L](X-terpy = 4[prime or minute]-substituted 2{,}2[prime or minute] : 6[prime or minute]{,}2[double prime]-terpyridine) have been prepared and characterised for a variety of electron-donating and -withdrawing substituent groups X."}
